def summarize_rnn(rnn, X_test, y_test, title_text = ''):
    
    classes = ['Hate', 'Neither', 'Offensive']
    cmap = plt.cm.Blues
    
    yhat = rnn.predict_classes(X_test)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, yhat, average = 'weighted')
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
    
    cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation = 'nearest', cmap = cmap)
    plt.title(f'{title_text} | Recall Score: {recall:.2f}')
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=0)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)
    
    fmt = '.2f'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.show()

def decode_sequence(sequence):
    sequence_decoded = []
    for _ in sequence:
        if _ == 0:
            pass
        else:
            word_decoded = int_to_word[_]
            sequence_decoded.append(word_decoded)
    return sequence_decoded

1. Dataset¶

The dataset used for this assignment contains ~15K tweets, collected from twitter, classified into 3 categories:

1) The tweet is not offensive. (neither)

2) The tweet uses offensive language but not hate speech. (offensive)

3) The tweet contains hate speech. (hate)

This dataset was collected by Thomas Davidson, Dana Warmsley, Michael Macy, and Ingmar Weber, for a paper / research project entitled 'Automated Hate Speech Detection and the Problem of Offensive Language[1].' This dataset was collected using crowd sourcing to collect and classify tweets containing hate speech, offensive language, and plain old tweets.

[1] Thomas Davidson, Dana Warmsley, Michael Macy, and Ingmar Weber. 2017. "Automated Hate Speech Detection and the Problem of Offensive Language." Proceedings of the 11th International Conference on Web and Social Media (ICWSM). The paper is available here https://aaai.org/ocs/index.php/ICWSM/ICWSM17/paper/view/15665

2. Business Understanding¶

Social media runs rampant with hate speech. Racial slurs, derogatory remarks, and targeted verbal abuse, can be found on across all social media platforms whether it be Facebook, Instagram, or Twitter, to name a few.

Across most major social media platforms there is some form of content censorship software backed by a supervisory team tasked with reviewing and removing content deemed inappropriate per the company's policy. A continual problem for these censorship algorithms is to distinguish hate speech from other instances of offensive language. Past lexical detection methods have suffered from poor performance because distinguishing between what is considered hate speech and what is considered offensive language is incredibly difficult for algorithms to accomplish. Such methods typically classify all messages containing certain words as either hate speech or offensive and thus have had difficulty distinguishing the two categories.

The dataset used for this assignment contains ~15K tweets collected from Twitter categorized by humans into 3 categories: tweets containing hate speech (hate), tweets containing offensive language (but is not considered hate speech)(offensive), and tweets that are not considered hate speech or offensive (neither).

The primary classification task of this algorithm is to determine if tweets contain hate speech. To achieve this objective, the algorithm needs to accomplish two other classification tasks. First, The algorithm needs to be able to distinguish between tweets containing hate speech, offensive language, or neither, and second, the algorithm needs to be able to distinguish between tweets containing hate speech and offensive language, which is where the majority of confusions occur.

In examining the classification task of this algorithm, the primary objective is to determine if tweets contain hate speech. In doing so, our primary user, Twitter, could deploy this algorithm on its platform and detect cases of tweets containing hate speech as they occur. The reason for the need to distinguish between hate speech and offensive language is because per company policy tweets containing hate speech may not be tolerated and removed from the platform immediately, while offensive tweets (tweets containing profanity) may be subject to review, however be allowed to be posted, due to peoples second amendment rights. If every tweet containing profanity was removed from the platform, Twitter's users would be limited in their right to freedom of speech and most likely find another place to voice their opinion. BBC news recently reported regarding Twitter "The challenge for the company has been to grapple with offensive content while not being seen to censor views[3]." Thus, in order to rid the platform of hate speech while still allowing individuals to freely express views, Twitter's ability to distinguish between hate speech and offensive content is of paramount importance[3]

The baseline algorithm I need to outperform, is the algorithm developed by Thomas Davidson, Dana Warmsley, Michael Macy, and Ingmar Weber, in their research paper, which was the primary inspiration for this lab. In their best performing algorithm they achieved an overall precision of 0.91, recall of 0.90, and F1 score of 0.90. The confusion matrix for their best performing model is shown in the figure below.

However, since the evaluation metric I found most appropriate for this classification task is recall, a recall score of 0.90 is my primary baseline. Thus, in order beat the competition and consider my algorithm deployable, I need to achieve a recall score of greater than 0.90.

$$ Recall\hspace{1mm}(r) = \frac{True\hspace{1mm} Positives} {True\hspace{1mm} Positives\hspace{1mm} + \hspace{1mm}False\hspace{1mm}Negatives} > 0.90$$

The targeted user for the algorithm developed in this assignment is Twitter, which has an estimated 10,000 tweets per day posted containing hate speech posted on its platform. However, this algorithm could be applied to any social media platform such as Google, Facebook, or Instagram.

3.5 Preprocessing¶

3.5.1 Padding the RNN Input Length¶

As seen in the tweets displayed above, the tweets in this dataset have varying length, as would be expected in practical circumstances. Due two the nature of varying length in tweets, in using RNNs to classify these tweets, I am faced with two options regarding how to handle the text input length to feed to the RNNs:

1) Feed the individual lengths of all the tweets into the RNN or

2) pad or truncate the length of the tweet to a constant value, making all tweets the same sequence length.

If I were to feed the individual lengths of all the tweet into the RNN, the RNN would need to have a varying input size and this would require continual updates to the computation graph under the keras hood making this cumbersome, time consuming, and inefficient.

Instead I chose to pad or truncate all the tweets to the same sequence length. With this, I must choose a constant value to pad or truncate all the tweets to. From the block of code below, it is seen that the minimum tweet length in this dataset is 4 characters and the maximum is 469 characters. At first I chose to use the maximum tweet length to encapsulate the entirety of all the tweets, however this caused training time be very slow and I did not notice outstanding performance using this. Therefore, I chose to use the average tweet length of 89 words as the value to pad or truncate all tweets to. This sped up training time significantly and did not seem to hinder classification performance.

3.3.2 Tokenize the Text¶

One cannot simply place words into an RNN and expect them to understand what is going on. We must find a way to speak the computers language and represent these sequences of words (what we humans call sentences) into sequences of something a computer would understand. In order to do this, we use a method called tokenization. Tokenizing is the act of breaking up a sequence of strings into pieces such as word, keywords, phrases, symbols, and other elements called tokens. In the process of tokenization, punctuation and other unnecessary characters are discarded from the strings. Once the sentences, or sequences of words, have been broken into their tokens, the tokenization gives each unique word, keyword, phrase, or symbol, a unique integer representation. Thus, sentences are now be represented by a series of integers which correspond to words, phrases, keywords, and symbols.

In the block of code below, a tokenizer object is created and fit on the tweets in this dataset. To understand what tokenzation actually does, an example of a tokenized tweet is shown below along with its decoding (which is shown after I create the dictionary mapping necessary for decoding).

4. Performance Evaluation Metric¶

In choosing an appropriate evaluation metric to evaluate algorithm performance, it is crucial to first understand the classification task and business application of this algorithm. As stated in the business case, the classification task of this algorithm is to determine if tweets containing hate speech. To do this, this algorithm must distinguish tweets containing hate speech from tweets containing offensive language (but not considered hate speech) and tweets that are not considered hate speech or offensive.

Let's consider an example to bring to light the evaluation metric that is most appropriate for this classification task. After the last presidential election, the people of America were divided and turned to social media to express political views and beliefs, and take out their frustrations. With this came a vast amount of tweets containing offensive language and hate speech, exchanged between people of opposite political parties. Twitter, now using our algorithm, combats this issue by running our algorithm through a tweet thread where this activity has been occurring. Due to their recent crackdown on hate speech, they want to remove all instances of tweets containing hate speech from the thread. Our algorithm detected numerous tweets containing hate speech and they are removed from the thread. Now, Twitter believes the thread is free of hate speech. But, what if our algorithm predicted that tweets containing hate speech were actually just offensive tweets, or neither. The hate speech tweets would have slipped through the cracks, and remained posted on the thread. The case described above illustrates the case of our algorithm predicting a false negative and this is our algorithms greatest pitfall.

Thus, the most appropriate performance evaluation metric for our algorithm is recall. That is, we want our algorithm to not miss any cases of tweets that may possibly contain hate speech, and therefore be inherently weary of predicting false negatives.

To further understand why recall is the most appropriate evaluation metric, let's examine the opposite case. The opposite evaluation metric to recall is precision, which is highly inappropriate in this case. Using precision to evaluate our algorithms performance, we would want our algorithm to be extremely certain in predicting that tweets contain hate speech, hence by weary of predicting false positives. In considering this, precision does not really seem appropriate to use in this scenario. That is, we do not necessarily care if the algorithm is overly cautious. Meaning it is favorable to have our algorithm predict cases of tweets containing hate speech, when they may just be offensive, or neither. This is because, as stated in the business case, most of these censorship algorithms are backed by a supervisory teams who review the content and decide if the tweets breaks company policy or not. Thus, while there is an associated cost with being overly cautious (giving the supervisory team more tweets to review), it is favorable to the contrary (missing the tweets all together).

To summarize the above, the most appropriate performance evaluation metric to measure algorithm performance is RECALL, defined mathematically as:

$$Recall\hspace{1mm}(r) = \frac{True\hspace{1mm} Positives} {True\hspace{1mm} Positives\hspace{1mm} + \hspace{1mm}False\hspace{1mm}Negatives}$$

Now that we have established the appropriate evaluation metric, with recall there are a few averaging options in which to consider to better tailor the recall score for this particular classification task. In choosing whether to 'micro', 'macro', or 'weighted' average the recall score, it is necessary to consider the class distribution of the dataset. Let's do so below:

From the pie chart above, it is seen that that the dataset contains significant class imbalance. 16.5% (Class 0) of the tweets contain hate speech, 50.1% (Class 1) are considered non-offensive, and 33.3% (Class 2) are considered offensive but not containing hate speech. Due to this, I chose to weighted average the recall score to account for the class imbalance issue. From the scikit-learn documentation, the weighted average calculates metrics for each label, and finds their average, weighted by the number of true instances for each label, thus it alters the macro average to account for class imbalance.

To summarize the above, the evaluation metric used to measure algorithm performance for the RNNs in this assignment is the weighted averaged recall score.

5. Method for Dividing Data into Training and Testing Splits¶

In choosing the appropriate method to divide our data into training and testing splits, let's look at three aspects of our algorithm: The overall dataset size, the class distribution of the dataset, and how our algorithm would be used in a deployed model at Twitter.

In addressing the amount of data available for training and testing, the dataset used for this assignment consists of 14,509 tweets. While this is a fairly large amount of data, in training RNNs for generalization performance it is helpful to have as much data as possible. Thus, in order to make efficient use of the 14,509 tweets in my dataset, I believe 10-Fold cross validation is the most appropriate method of dividing the data into training and testing splits. Using 10-Fold cross validation ensures the RNNs in this assignment will be trained and tested over vast amounts of data and therefore be adequately measured in terms of generalization performance.

Furthermore, using stratification techniques in the 10-Fold cross validation method, allows me to reflect the class imbalance in the dataset in the training and testing folds. Stratification is essential in this scenario because without it certain folds of the dataset could be entirely comprised of tweets that are not considered hate speech or offensive, for instance, and thus perturb our algorithms classification task and training. Thus, in order to ensure that the class imbalance is represented in each fold of the training and testing splits, stratified 10-Fold cross validation now becomes the most appropriate method for dividing the data into training and testing splits.

This method of cross validation accurately represents how this algorithm would be used in deployed model at Twitter because with the 500 million tweets posted per day and 10,000 of those on average cases of hate speech, the algorithm would have access to to immense amounts of data. Thus training and testing the algorithm over as much data as I can given the size constraint of my dataset, which is what K-Fold cross validation does, mirrors as best I can the actual amount of data the algorithm would be exposed to.

However, it should be noted that due to the time it takes to train the RNNs, instead of using 10-Fold cross validation, I truncated this to 3-Fold cross validation to speed up the training time. While the algorithm will be trained and tested over a lesser number of folds, we can still achieve an general idea of generalization performance.

6. Embeddings¶

An essential part of Natural Language Processing (NLP) is word embeddings. Word embeddings serve as a way to reduce the dimensionality of the vocabulary in a text corpus by mapping them into a vectorized form. Dimensionality reduction is crucial in NLP as the scope of the English vocabulary is huge (for this particular example, not to be egocentric). This is because for use in RNNs the tokenized text must first undergo one more processing step: one hot encoding. Thus, each token will now be individually represented as a one hot encoded vector. However, with the one hot encoding, we are faced with the curse of dimensionality. For example in this case, there are 29,342 unique tokens in the tweets I am working with. When these values are one hot encoded we end up with a 29,342 x 29,342 size vocabulary. This is enormous! Also, completely unrealistic for any machine learning algorithm we work with. To combat this dimensionality curse, we can use word embeddings. With word embeddings we can represent our vocabulary by a reduced set a vectors pertaining to a subset of words (meaning one vector could actually correspond to multiple words). Where the size of our word embedding will now determine the total dimensionality of our data.

For use in the RNNs below, I chose to use the Stanford Glove embeddings, which is a pre-trained word embedding matrix for use in NLP algorithms. Thanks Stanford! With the Glove embeddings there were four different sizes of embeddings to choose from 100, 200, 300, 500. For this lab I chose to use the 100 dimension glove embedding. This choice was a judgment call on my behalf, however it was supported by the fact that I believed the language one would use while tweeting may lack in complexity and vocabulary size. For instance, as opposed to the language an NLP algorithm would see based on novel text. With the 100 dimension word embedding, the dimensionality of the vocabulary is reduced from 860,952,964 to 2,934,200.

    values = line.split()

    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype = 'float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()

print(f'Found {len(embeddings_index)} word vectors')

7. Modeling¶

In the section below, I will investigate two types of Recurrent Neural Networks architectures, namely a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) and a Long Short Term Memory (LSTM). Both architectures will be primarily tested and hyperparameters will be tuned to attempt to improve performance. At the end of this exploration, the architectures will be compared and a best performing model will be determined. Once the best performing model has been found, I will explore a chained RNN architectures using my best performing model.

It should be noted that the RNNs below were trained only once over the course of two weeks due to trained time. Thus, you will see the blocks of code containing the architectures and the cross validation loops have not been run this time. However, they have been trained and the necessary results saved.

7.1 Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU)¶

The first RNN architecture I will look at is a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU). GRUs aim to solve the vanishing gradient problem which plagues standard RNNs. To solve the vanishing gradient problem, GRUs use update and reset gates. In essence these gates are basically vectors that decide what information should be passed to the output. Another nice feature about GRUs is they typically require less data to train, which is why I chose to start with them.

In [44]:
def create_gru():
    gru = Sequential()
    gru.add(embedding_layer)
    gru.add(GRU(100, dropout = 0.2, recurrent_dropout = 0.2))
    gru.add(Dense(n_classes, activation = 'sigmoid'))
    return gru

7.1.1 GRU Hyperparamter Tuning¶

In the section below, I will explore tuning hyperparameters in the GRU to see which set of parameters yields the highest recall score. I chose to perform the hyperparameter tuning using a series of for loop because the KerasClassifier method was unnecessarily tedious. In the optimization code below, you will notice I trained the model using the X_train, and y_train_ohe datasets from above, and not over the 3-Fold cross validation method I argued as appropriate for this classification algorithm. This is because I am solely concerned with boosting performance here and examining the interplay between parameters of the GRU, not in generalization performance. That being said, once the optimal parameters are found, which yield the highest recall score, they will be placed into the GRU model and evaluated appropriately for generalization performance using the 3-Fold cross validation. Do to the amount of time it took perform the hyperparameter tuning, I chose to run the fit method for 10 epochs and assumed that the parameters to reach the highest recall score in 10 epochs were the optimal set of parameters. Again, when I place the parameters in the GRU model it will be run for a greater number of epochs.

In [ ]:
def create_gru_optimized(cells, dropout, activation, loss, optimizer):
    gru_optimized = Sequential()
    gru_optimized.add(embedding_layer)
    gru_optimized.add(GRU(cells, dropout = dropout, recurrent_dropout = dropout))
    gru_optimized.add(Dense(n_classes, activation = activation))
    gru_optimized.compile(loss = loss, optimizer = optimizer, metrics = ['accuracy'])
    return gru_optimized

# Code Reference: https://github.com/eclarson/MachineLearningNotebooks/blob/master/13.%20RNN%20Basics.ipynb
# The code above was adapted from Eric Larson's Notebook RNN Basics which can be found at the url above
In [ ]:
gru_optimization_dict = dict()
cells = [50, 100]
dropout = [0.1, 0.2, 0.4,]
activation = ['sigmoid', 'softmax']
loss = ['categorical_crossentropy']
optimizer = ['adam', 'rmsprop']
batch_size = [100, 500]

for c in cells:
    for d in dropout:
        for a in activation:
            for l in loss:
                for o in optimizer:
                    for b in batch_size:
                        gru_optim = create_gru_optimized(cells=c,
                                                         dropout=d,
                                                         activation=a,
                                                         loss = l,
                                                         optimizer = o)

                        gru_optim.fit(X_train, y_train_ohe, epochs = 10, verbose = 1, batch_size = b)
                        yhat = gru_optim.predict_classes(X_test)
                        recall = recall_score(y_test, yhat, average = 'weighted')
                        gru_optimization_dict[recall] = (c,d,a,l,o,b)

Here we can see a flaw in my methodology for tuning the hyperparameters. This is most likely attributed to the small amount of dropout in the GRU. When I was performing the hyperparameter tuning, I chose to select the parameters that gave the highest recall score after 10 epochs, which resulted in a dropout of 0.1 or 10%. However, as can be seen above, by letting the network actually train for a reasonable number of epochs, using such low dropout in the network causes the model to over-fit the training data and therefore generalize poorly to the validation set.

Below, let's tune the dropout parameter a little more and see if we can fix this issue.

7.2 Long Short Term Memory (LSTM)¶

The next RNN architecture I will explore is a Long Short Term Memory (LSTM). LSTM units are composed of a cell, input gate, output gate, and a forget gate. The purpose of the LSTM cell is to memorize values over arbitrary time intervals, it deems pertinent to the classification task. Each gate in the LSTM cell acts like a neuron in a typical multi-layer perceptron, each regulating inputs and outputs. LSTMs also aim to solve the vanishing gradient problem of standard RNNs.

Again I will start with a simple RNN to get a baseline performance and then tune hyperparameters accordingly.

In [ ]:
def create_lstm():

8. RNN Comparision¶

In the section below, I will compare the performance in terms of the evaluation metric (recall), of the 5 RNN architectures explored above. I begin by performing a rough comparison of the 5 models and with that, select what I believe are the two best performing models. Once the two best performing models have been determined, I will perform a T-Test and examine an ROC curve to determine the winner of the two.

8.2 T-Test¶

Above we established that the Dropout_Optimized_GRU was the best performing RNN with the Optimized_GRU coming in second place via the average recall score and standard deviation is recall scores over the cross validation loops for the RNN architectures. Now, let's determine if we can statistically determine which is the better RNN.

To statistically compare the performance of the RNNs, I will perform a T-Test. More specifically, I will approximate the bounds using the folds of the cross fold validation to get a mean and variance of the recall scores for the RNNs. I believe this is the most appropriate means of generating confidence intervals because both models were trained using the same data. For the T-Test, I will use a t value of 2.26 and k = 10 (note that this is lowercase k and not capital K, which indicated the number of folds in the cross validation).

If the resulting confidence interval between the two RNNs does not include 0, then statistically, with 95% confidence, I can say that the Dropout_Optimized_GRU is the better RNN.

In [58]:
recall_score_gru_optimized = np.asarray(gru_optimized_recall_list)
recall_score_gru_dropout_optimized = np.asarray(gru_dropout_optimized_recall_list)
In [59]:
k = 10
t = 2.26 / np.sqrt(k)

e = (1 - recall_score_gru_dropout_optimized) - (1 - recall_score_gru_optimized)
stdtot = np.std(e)
dbar = np.mean(e)
print('Confidence Interval:', dbar - t * stdtot, '-->', dbar + t * stdtot)

Confidence Interval: -0.005257881866407401 --> 0.0012973839408743364

In statistically examining the performance of the two RNNs above, I cannot say with 95% confidence which is the better RNN architecture due to the fact that the resulting confidence interval, from the T-Test, between the two includes 0.

However, let's not give up yet. Let's use another model evaluation criteria we have looked at and see if we can determine a winner.

8.3 ROC and AUC¶

Below, we are going to look at the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and the Area Under the Curve (AUC) as another method to compare the two best RNN architectures. ROC curves are useful tools which aid in selecting classification models based on their performance with respect to the False Positive Rate and True Positive Rate. ROC curves are constructed by shifting the decision threshold of the classifier, and counting the number of True Positives and False Positives both above and below the threshold. The diagonal of an ROC curve represents random guessing, while a perfect classifier would have a True Positive Rate of 1 and a False Positive Rate if 0, both represented in the ROC curve below. Once an ROC curve has been constructed, more information can be derived from the AUC to characterize the classification performance of a model, with a greater AUC commonly indicating a better model[4].

Below, lets compute and graphically examine the ROC and AUC of Dropout_Optimized_GRU and the Optimized_GRU and see if we can determine which is the better classifier.

[4] Raschka, Sebastian & Mirkalili, Vahid. Python Machine Learning.

By adding a second recurrent chain, the output sequence from the first GRU becomes the input sequence to the second GRU, thus 'chaining' RNNs together.

9.1 Fix Overfitting¶

Let's not give up on this architecture just yet. I believe the reason for the poor performance of the chained RNN above is due to the immense over-fitting of the training data. This all stems from the original hyperparameter tuning for the GRU that stated the optimial dropout was 0.1. Below let's throw this aside and see if we can fix the over-fitting issue by increasing the dropout in both GRUs.

11. Visualization of Word Embeddings¶

In the section below, dimensionality reduction techniques are used in an attempt to reflect and interpret meaning from the word embeddings used in the RNNs above. That is, in the code below, I will use T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) dimensionality reduction to visualize the word embeddings of a subset of words in the vocabulary of tweets in the dataset. Using t-SNE I will reduce the dimensionality of the word vectors in the glove embeddings to a dimensionality of 2, which can be more easily visualized and understood. With these visualizations, I will interpret what aspect of language is reflected in each dimension of the t-SNE embedding.

With t-SNE there are few hyperparameters that must be addressed and made sense of in relation to the data at hand, which are perplexity, n_components, and n_iter. I chose to set the perplexity to a value of 100 because the embeddings represent a complex vector embeddings of words in the tweet vocabulary. I chose to set this to a higher value because I believe the embedding data to be more complicated than a standard table of numeric values (or something of the sorts). From the scikit learn documentation on t-SNE, perplexity is related to the number of nearest neighbors that is used in other manifold learning algorithms, thus larger datasets usually require a larger perplexity. Next, the number of components (n_components) is the number of dimensions I want to reflect in the embedded space of the t-SNE dimensionality reduction method, which is 2. Lastly, the number of iterations I set to a very high value simply because the starter code I looked at had the iterations set high.

11.1 A Small Subset¶

I chose to begin with a very simple example to get things up and running. The classic machine learning example everyone tends to use for word embedding visualization is man, women, queen, king. Here I chose to stick with a similar convention but instead use boy, girl, woman, man. Let's see what the embedded space output looks like.

In [70]:
word_subset = ['boy', 'girl', 'woman', 'man']
tokens = []
labels = []

for word in word_subset:
    tokens.append(embeddings_index[word])
    labels.append(word)
    

tsne_model = TSNE(perplexity = 100, n_components = 2, n_iter = 2500, random_state = 1)
new_values = tsne_model.fit_transform(tokens)

x = []
y = []

for value in new_values:
    x.append(value[0])
    y.append(value[1])
    
plt.figure(figsize = (20,10))
for i in range(len(x)):
    plt.scatter(x[i], y[i])
    plt.annotate(labels[i], xy = (x[i], y[i]), xytext = (5,2), 
                 textcoords = 'offset points', ha = 'right', va = 'bottom')

plt.xlabel('Dimension 1')
plt.ylabel('Dimension 2')
plt.xticks([])
plt.yticks([])
plt.title('Word Embedding Relations')
plt.show()

For this particular subset of vocabulary, we can see a very interesting relationship in the word embeddings using t-SNE dimensionality reduction. Dimension 1 seems to capture temporal relations or age, while Dimension 2 seems to capture gender. I believe this to be accurate because in examining dimension 1 we see that both woman and man are located on the left hand side of the axis, while girl and boy are both located on the right hand side of the axis. This reflects the age of the individual because when people are young they tend to be referred to as girls or boys and when people are older they tend to be referred to as men or women. Thus Dimension 1 could accurately take on integer labels indicating age with in a descending manner, from left to right. Examining Dimension 2, we see that both woman and girl are located on the upper-most half of the axis and man and boy are located in the bottom-most half of the axis. Thus this axis somewhat captures a persons gender to a degree, and could accurately be labeled female in the upper-most half and male in the bottom-most half.

The spacial relations reflected in these dimensions almost seem consistent with one another. For instance the directionality and separation between woman and man and girl and boy seem roughly identical at a glance. Below, I am going to attempt to find the vector difference between woman and man and see if we can navigate from boy to girl via that same vector!

In [71]:
# Create tuples of coordinates for each point
boy = (x[0], y[0])
girl = (x[1], y[1])
woman = (x[2], y[2])
man = (x[3], y[3])
In [72]:
# Get the vector difference between man and woman
print(f'Vector difference between woman and man: {((abs(woman[0] - man[0]),abs(woman[1] - man[1])))}')

Vector difference between woman and man: (52.64203, 181.92725)

Now let's use these values to try to navigate from girl to boy and see how close we can get!

In [73]:
print(f'Coordinates obtained by adding vector difference to girl: {((girl[0] + 52.64203), girl[1] - 181.92725)}')
print(f'Coordinates for boy: {boy}')

Coordinates obtained by adding vector difference to girl: (516.7230236523437, 129.8437155761719)
Coordinates for boy: (516.7231, 129.84358)

Look at that! By adding the vector difference obtained traveling from Woman to Man to Girl, we almost exactly arrive at Boy! This shows tremendous correlation between the relationship of boy and girl and woman and man.

In this more complex embedding space, using a greater subset of vocabulary, we do not see the same relationships above hold. However there are a few notable interesting things going on here. 11. Closing Thoughts¶

The primary purpose of the RNNs developed in this assignment was to classify hate speech on Twitter. The baseline comparison I wanted to beat was that achieved by Thomas Davidson, Dana Warmsley, Michael Macy, and Ingmar Weber, in their paper and exploration of this same task. Unfortunately none of the RNNs in this assignment came close to the performance needed to be considered a deployable algorithm. The highest recall score the RNNs I developed were able to obtain was around ~79%, which is 11% lower than it needed to be to beat my competition. Because of this I would not deploy this algorithm to be used by Twitter.
